            <div type="edition">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/> 
                    <persName>
                        <name type="praenomen" key="Marcus"><expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>arco</ex></expan></name> 
                        <name type="gentilicium" key="Vibius">Vibio</name> 
                        <persName>
                            <name type="praenomen" key="Marcus"><expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>arci</ex></expan></name>
                        </persName> <expan><abbr>fil</abbr><ex>io</ex></expan> 
                        <name type="cognomen" key="Liberalis">Li<supplied reason="lost">b</supplied>erali</name>
                    </persName> 
                    <expan><abbr>praet</abbr><ex>ori</ex></expan> 
                    <persName>
                        <name type="praenomen" key="Marcus"><expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>arcus</ex></expan></name> 
                        <name type="gentilicium" key="Vibius">Vibius</name> 
                        <name type="cognomen" key="Agesilaus">Agesilaus</name>
                    </persName> iunior nutricio suo <expan><abbr>fec</abbr><ex>it</ex></expan>.
                </ab>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Marcus Vibius Agesilaus the younger made this for his guardian Marcus Vibius Liberalis, son of Marcus, praetor.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The letters of the inscription are evenly sized and evenly spaced, with a tilde-shaped interpunct between each word. 
                    The only exception to this rule is in the space following Vibio, where there is a single dot placed between the last letter of the 
                    word and the tilde-shaped interpunct. The diameter of the dot is approximately even with the width of the tilde-shaped interpunct, 
                    and its edges are smooth, indicating that it is original to the inscription rather than subsequent damage. The letters of the inscription are wide and have serifs.</p>
                <p>The inscription running along the bottom of the front face names Marcus Vibius Liberalis as the deceased, for whom the younger 
                    Marcus Vibius Agesilaus made the sarcophagus. The relationship between the two men is explained by the word nutricio, indicating guardianship; 
                    the translation provided by the MFA translates nutricio as foster-father. Prosopographic evidence suggests that nutricius describes a close 
                    relationship between a younger individual and an adult individual who is playing a protective and parental role, but where biological relation 
                    is not implied. This type of relationship is illustrated by the case of Gnaeus Cornelius Atimetus, a freedman whose epitaph states that 
                    he was the nutricius of the son of Cossus Cornelius Lentulus Gaetulicus, Gnaeus Cornelius Lentulus Gaetulicus (described in PIR2 1392; Bodel, 23). 
                    </p>
                <p>A military diploma from 166 CE (CIL 16, 121) states that Marcus Vibius Liberalis was consul that year. This would suggest that the sarcophagus 
                    dates to the late second century or early third century CE. The MFA dates the sarcophagus to ca. 215-225 CE, which is plausible based on the consular 
                    dating from the diploma.</p>
                    <p>The Marble of the sarcophagus appears to have been quarried in Proconnesus.
                </p>
            </div>
            

